{META_DATA}: "FORREST GUMP"
{META_DATA}: Screenplay by
{META_DATA}: Eric Roth
{META_DATA}: Based on a novel by
{META_DATA}: Winston Groom
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. A SAVANNAH STREET - DAY (1981)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A feather floats through the air.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The falling feather.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A city, Savannah, is revealed in the background.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The feather floats down toward the city below.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The feather drops down toward the street below, as people walk past and cars drive by, and nearly lands on a man's shoulder.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He walks across the street, causing the feather to be whisked back on its journey.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The feather floats above a stopped car.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The car drives off right as the feather floats down toward the street.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The feather floats under a passing car, then is sent flying back up in the air.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A MAN sits on a bus bench.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The feather floats above the ground and finally lands on the man's mudsoaked shoe.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The man reached down and picks up the feather.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His name is FORREST GUMP.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks at the feather oddly, moves aside a box of chocolates from an old suitcase, then opens the case.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Inside the old suitcase are an assortment of clothes, a pingpong paddle, toothpaste and other personal items.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest pulls out a book titled "Curious George," then places the feather inside the book.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest closes the suitcase.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Something in his eyes reveals that Forrest may not be all there.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest looks right as the sound of an arriving bus is heard.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A bus pulls up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest remains on the bus bench as the bus continues on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A BLACK WOMAN in a nurse's outfit steps up and sits down at the bus bench next to Forrest.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The nurse begins to read a magazine as Forrest looks at her.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORREST
{DIALOGUE}: Hello.
{DIALOGUE}: My name's Forrest Gump.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He opens a box of chocolates and holds it out for the nurse.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORREST
{DIALOGUE}: You want a chocolate?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The nurse shakes her head, a bit apprehensive about this strange man next to her.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORREST
{DIALOGUE}: I could eat about a million and a half of these.
{DIALOGUE}: My momma always said, "Life was like a box of chocolates.
{DIALOGUE}: You never know what you're gonna get."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest eats a chocolate as he looks down at the nurse's shoes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORREST
{DIALOGUE}: Those must be comfortable shoes.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll bet you could walk all day in shoes like that and not feel a thing.
{DIALOGUE}: I wish I had shoes like that.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BLACK WOMAN
{DIALOGUE}: My feet hurt.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORREST
{DIALOGUE}: Momma always says there's an awful lot you could tell about a person by their shoes.
{DIALOGUE}: Where they're going.
{DIALOGUE}: Where they've been.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The black woman stares at Forrest as he looks down at his own shoes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORREST
{DIALOGUE}: I've worn lots of shoes.
{DIALOGUE}: I bet if I think about it real hard I could remember my first pair of shoes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest closes his eyes tightly.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORREST
{DIALOGUE}: Momma said they'd take my anywhere.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. COUNTRY DOCTOR'S OFFICE - GREENBOW, ALABAMA - DAY
{META_DATA}: (1951)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A little boy closes his eyes tightly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is young Forrest as he sits in a doctor's office.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORREST (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: She said they was my magic shoes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest has been fitted with orthopedic shoes and metal leg braces.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DOCTOR
{DIALOGUE}: All right, Forrest, you can open your eyes now.
{DIALOGUE}: Let's take a little walk around.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The doctor sets Forrest down on its feet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest walks around stiffly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest's mother, MRS. GUMP, watches him as he clanks around the room awkwardly.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DOCTOR
{DIALOGUE}: How do those feel?
{DIALOGUE}: His legs are strong, Mrs. Gump.
{DIALOGUE}: As strong as I've ever seen.
{DIALOGUE}: But his back is as crooked as a politician.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest walks foreground past the doctor and Mrs. Gump.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DOCTOR
{DIALOGUE}: But we're gonna straighten him right up now, won't we, Forrest?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A loud thud is heard as, outside, Forrest falls.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. GUMP
{DIALOGUE}: Forrest!
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. GREENBOW, ALABAMA
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Gump and young Forrest walk across the street.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest walks stiffly next to his mother.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORREST (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Now, when I was a baby, Momma named me after the great Civil War hero, General Nathan Bedford Forrest...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. RURAL ALABAMA
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A black and white photo of General Nathan Bedford Forrest.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The photo turns into live action as the General dons a hooded sheet over his head.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The General is in full Ku Klux Klan garb, including his horse.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The General rides off, followed by a large group of Klan members dressed in full uniform.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORREST (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: She said we was related to him in some way.
{DIALOGUE}: And, what he did was, he started up this club called the Ku Klux Klan.
{DIALOGUE}: They'd all dress up in their robes and their bedsheets and act like a bunch of ghosts or spooks or something.
{DIALOGUE}: They'd even put bedsheets on their horses and ride around.
{DIALOGUE}: And anyway, that's how I got my name.
{DIALOGUE}: Forrest Gump.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. GREENBOW
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Gump and Forrest walk across the street.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORREST (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Momma said that the Forrest part was to remind me that sometimes we all do things that, well, just don't make no sense.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest stops suddenly as his brace gets stuck.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest's brace is caught in a gutter grate.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Gump bends down and tries to free Forrest.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Two old cronies sit in front of a barber shop and watch.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. GUMP
{DIALOGUE}: Just wait, let me get it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Gump struggles to pull the stuck brace from the grate.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. GUMP
{DIALOGUE}: Let me get it.
{DIALOGUE}: Wait, get it this way.
{DIALOGUE}: Hold on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest pulls his foot out of the grate.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. GUMP
{DIALOGUE}: All right.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Gump helps Forrest up onto the sidewalk.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She looks up and notices the two old man.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. GUMP
{DIALOGUE}: Oooh.
{DIALOGUE}: All right.
{DIALOGUE}: What are you all staring at?
{DIALOGUE}: Haven't you ever seen a little boy with braces on his legs before?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Gump and Forrest walk along the sidewalk past the two old men.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Gump holds tightly onto Forrest's hand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. GUMP
{DIALOGUE}: Don't ever let anybody tell you they're better than you, Forrest.
{DIALOGUE}: If God intended everybody to be the same, he'd have given us all braces on our legs.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORREST (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Momma always had a way of explaining things so I could understand them.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. OAK ALLEY/THE GUMP BOARDING HOUSE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Gump and Forrest walk along a dirt road.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A row of mailboxes stands left.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORREST (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: We lived about a quarter mile of Route 17, about a half mile from the town of Greenbow, Alabama.
{DIALOGUE}: That's in the county of Greenbow.
{DIALOGUE}: Our house had been in Momma's family since her grandpa's grandpa's grandpa had come across the ocean about a thousand years ago.
{DIALOGUE}: Something like that.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Gump and Forrest walk along the Gump Boarding House driveway.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORREST (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Since it was just me and Momma and we had all these empty rooms, Momma decided to let those rooms out.
{DIALOGUE}: Mostly to people passing through.
{DIALOGUE}: Like from, oh, Mobile, Montgomery, place like that.
{DIALOGUE}: That's how me and Mommy got money.
{DIALOGUE}: Mommy was a real smart lady.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. GUMP
{DIALOGUE}: Remember what I told you, Forrest.
{DIALOGUE}: You're no different than anybody else is.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Gump heads Forrest to the porch.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She bends down to look Forrest in the eye.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. GUMP
{DIALOGUE}: Did you hear what I said, Forrest?
{DIALOGUE}: You're the same as everybody else.
{DIALOGUE}: You are no different.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. ELEMENTARY SCHOOL / PRINCIPAL'S OFFICE - DAY
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PRINCIPAL
{DIALOGUE}: Your boy's... different, Mrs. Gump.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, his I.Q. is seventy-five.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. GUMP
{DIALOGUE}: Well, we're all different, Mr. Hancock.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The principal sighs, then stands up.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HALLWAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest sits outside the principal's office and waits.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORREST (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: She wanted me to have the finest education, so she took me to the Greenbow County Central School.
{DIALOGUE}: I met the principal and all.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The principal stands in front of Mrs. Gump.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest, sitting left, listens.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PRINCIPAL
{DIALOGUE}: I want to show you something, Mrs. Gump.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, this is normal.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The principal holds up a chart with a designations according to I.Q. and points to the center of the graph, labeled "Normal."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A red line below the normal area is labeled "State Acceptance."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The principal points to the section below the acceptance line labeled "Below."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PRINCIPAL
{DIALOGUE}: Forrest is right here.
{DIALOGUE}: The state requires a minimum I.Q. of eighty to attend public school, Mrs. Gump.
{DIALOGUE}: He's gonna have to go to a special school.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, he'll be just fine.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. GUMP
{DIALOGUE}: What does normal mean, anyway?
{DIALOGUE}: He might be a bit on the slow side, but my boy Forrest is going to get the same opportunities as everyone else.
{DIALOGUE}: He's not going to some special school to learn to how to re-tread tires.
{DIALOGUE}: We're talking about five little points here.
{DIALOGUE}: There must be something can be done.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HALLWAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest sits outside the principal's office.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PRINCIPAL
{DIALOGUE}: We're a progressive school system.
{DIALOGUE}: We don't want to see anybody left behind.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. PRINCIPAL'S OFFICE
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PRINCIPAL
{DIALOGUE}: Is there a Mr. Gump, Mrs. Gump?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. GUMP
{DIALOGUE}: He's on vacation.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. GUMP BOARDING HOUSE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest sits on a swing outside the house.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Loud organic male grunts are heard coming from inside the house.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest sits on the swing as the grunts continue.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The principal steps out of the Gump House and wipes the sweat from his face.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest is sitting on the porch.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PRINCIPAL
{DIALOGUE}: Well, your momma sure does care about your schooling, son.
{DIALOGUE}: Mm-mm-mm.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The principal wipes the sweat from his neck, then looks back at Forrest.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PRINCIPAL
{DIALOGUE}: You don't say much, do you?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest grunts, imitating him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The principal, embarrassed, turns and walks away.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. GUMP BOARDING HOUSE/FORREST'S BEDROOM
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Gump reads from the book "Curious George" as Forrest sits on the bed and listens.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. GUMP
{DIALOGUE}: Finally, he had to try it.
{DIALOGUE}: It looked easy, but, oh, what happened.
{DIALOGUE}: First there...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORREST
{DIALOGUE}: Momma, what's vacation mean?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. GUMP
{DIALOGUE}: Vacation?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORREST
{DIALOGUE}: Where Daddy went?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. GUMP
{DIALOGUE}: Vacation's when you go somewhere, and you don't ever come back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest lies down on his bed and looks up.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORREST (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Anyway, I guess you could say me and Momma was on our own.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. GUMP BOARDING HOUSE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A cab driver closes the trunk of the car as two women walk toward the house.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A milkman steps down from the porch.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORREST (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: But we didn't mind.
{DIALOGUE}: Our house was never empty.
{DIALOGUE}: There was always folks comin' and goin'.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. GUMP (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Suppa.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. GUMP BOARDING HOUSE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Gump steps forward and speaks to all the boarders.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. GUMP
{DIALOGUE}: It's suppa, everyone.
{DIALOGUE}: Forrest...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A MAN WITH A CANE steps left across the hall.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAN WITH CANE
{DIALOGUE}: My, my.
{DIALOGUE}: That sure looks special.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Gump looks into a sitting room and informs the boarders about dinner.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. GUMP
{DIALOGUE}: Gentlemen, would you care to join us for supper?
{DIALOGUE}: Hurry up and get it before the flies do.
{DIALOGUE}: I prefer you don't smoke that cigar so close to mealtime.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORREST (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Sometimes we had so many people stayin' with us that every room was filled with travelers.
{DIALOGUE}: You know, folks livin' out of their suitcases, and hat cases, and sample cases.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. GUMP
{DIALOGUE}: Well, you go ahead and start.
{DIALOGUE}: I can't find Forrest.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Gump walks up the stairs.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. GUMP
{DIALOGUE}: Forrest... Forrest...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORREST (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: One time a young man was staying with us, and he had him a guitar case.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Gump looks into Forrest's room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She hears singing coming from another room and walks over to a closed door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Gump opens the door, revealing a young man with long sideburns as he plays the guitar and sings.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest holds onto a broom and dances oddly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The young man is ELVIS PRESLEY.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELVIS PRESLEY
{META_DATA}: (sings)
{DIALOGUE}: "Well, you ain't never caught a rabbit, and you ain't no friend of mine."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest's legs rock back and forth to the guitar.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. GUMP
{DIALOGUE}: Forrest!
{DIALOGUE}: I told you not to bother this nice young man.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELVIS
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, no, that's all right, ma'am.
{DIALOGUE}: I was just showin' him a thing or two on the guitar here.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. GUMP
{DIALOGUE}: All right, but your supper's ready if y'all want to eat.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELVIS
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, that sounds good.
{DIALOGUE}: Thank you, ma'am.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Gump leaves and closes the door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Elvis sits back down.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest stands left, and looks himself in a mirror.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELVIS
{DIALOGUE}: Say, man, show me that crazy little walk you just did there.
{DIALOGUE}: Slow it down some.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest begins to dance again as Elvis plays the guitar and sings.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELVIS
{META_DATA}: (sings)
{DIALOGUE}: "You ain't nothin' but a hound, hound dog..."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORREST (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: I liked that guitar.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest dances as he watches himself in the mirror.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORREST (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: It sounded good.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELVIS
{META_DATA}: (sings)
{DIALOGUE}: "...cryin' all the time"
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Forrest rocks up and down on his braced legs, then begins to step.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELVIS
{META_DATA}: (sings)
{DIALOGUE}: "You ain't nothin' but a hound dog..."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORREST (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: I started moving around to the music, swinging my hips.
{DIALOGUE}: This one night me and Momma...
